      "id": "2022Mains_25JulMorning_Chem_Q1",
      "year": 2022,
      "paper": "25JulMorning",
      "question_number": 1,
      "question_text": "SO₂Cl₂ on reaction with excess of water results into acidic mixture SO₂Cl₂ + 2H₂O → H₂SO₄ + 2HCl. 16 moles of NaOH is required for the complete neutralisation of the resultant acidic mixture. The number of moles of SO₂Cl₂ used is:",
      "question_type": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "topic": "Physical Chemistry - Stoichiometry",
      "sub_topic": "Acid-base neutralisation",
      "correct_answer": "C",
      "solution_summary": "Let n(SO₂Cl₂) = x. n(H₂SO₄) = x, n(HCl) = 2x. n(H⁺) = 4x. For neutralisation: n(H⁺) = n(OH⁻) → 4x = 16 → x = 4.",
